03:08.449 --> 03:09.450
Barnes: Aww!Oh.

03:09.493 --> 03:11.234
You better
sweep that up, Messy.

03:11.278 --> 03:13.367
Maddox: [ Chuckles ]

03:13.410 --> 03:16.152
Seriously, Duval,
make them clean that up.

03:16.196 --> 03:18.110
Fire Zaddy, 12:00.

03:18.154 --> 03:19.242
Hey.

03:19.286 --> 03:20.939
Hey.

03:20.983 --> 03:23.290
What are you doing here?Working.

03:23.333 --> 03:24.291
You're the sub?

03:24.334 --> 03:25.640
You're the captain.

03:25.683 --> 03:26.467
You don't know
who's subbing?

03:26.510 --> 03:28.251
I'm the acting captain,

03:28.295 --> 03:30.862
and I had my lieutenant
sign the approval.

03:30.906 --> 03:32.168
Last time that'll happen.

03:32.212 --> 03:33.778
Well, I can be
professional.

03:33.822 --> 03:36.259
If you can't,
that's a you problem.

03:36.303 --> 03:38.479
♪♪

03:38.522 --> 03:40.959
Hey, Mom,
it's me -- again.

03:41.003 --> 03:42.613
Could you please
call me back?

03:42.657 --> 03:44.006
[ Door closes ]

03:44.049 --> 03:45.094
Hey.

03:45.137 --> 03:46.269
Where do we keep
the toolbox?

03:46.313 --> 03:47.836
What kind of tools
are we looking for?

03:47.879 --> 03:50.186
Uh, the -- the kind
you keep in a toolbox.

03:50.230 --> 03:52.144
I think there are some
in the kitchen cabinet.

03:52.188 --> 03:53.363
Okay, good.Should I even ask?

03:53.407 --> 03:55.017
The towel rack's broken.

03:55.060 --> 03:56.888
Did you call Gibson?To fix the towel rack?

03:56.932 --> 03:58.455
No, to come over.

03:58.499 --> 04:00.022
Wrong one.
Wrong one again.

04:02.067 --> 04:03.373
He hasn't been to work
since Thanksgiving.

04:03.417 --> 04:05.157
We're worried about him,
and he could use a buddy.

04:05.201 --> 04:06.594
Okay, then
you can call him.

04:06.637 --> 04:08.117
I gotta go make sure
that my mom hasn't

04:08.160 --> 04:09.510
murdered my father
and fled the country.

04:09.553 --> 04:11.642
Just call him. It could be
good for both of you.

04:12.904 --> 04:14.689
Uh, hold on, you --

04:14.732 --> 04:15.994
This is you trying
to sneakily get me

04:16.038 --> 04:17.822
to not be alone because
you're worried about me,

04:17.866 --> 04:19.302
but you're pretending
to worry about Gibson.

04:19.346 --> 04:20.434
Mm.
Yeah.

04:20.477 --> 04:22.131
I can be worried
about you both.

04:22.174 --> 04:25.352
[ Smooches ]
I'm a multitasker.

04:25.395 --> 04:26.788
[ Door lock clicks ]

04:26.831 --> 04:28.268
[ Lively music playing
over radio ]

04:28.311 --> 04:33.969
♪♪

04:34.012 --> 04:35.579
Um...

04:36.928 --> 04:38.800
Carina, am I in
the right apartment?

04:40.367 --> 04:43.283
Sorpresa.

04:43.326 --> 04:46.721
You are supposed
to be at work.

04:46.764 --> 04:48.723
I'm not working
for the next two days.

04:48.766 --> 04:49.941
[ Gasps ] Oh, w-why?

04:49.985 --> 04:51.856
Because we're making
some homemade porn?

04:51.900 --> 04:52.857
No.

04:52.901 --> 04:54.294
It is romance.Mm.

04:54.337 --> 04:55.773
Not porn.

04:57.427 --> 05:01.344
But there is a lot of red.

05:01.388 --> 05:03.564
We're making a baby,
and I want to have

05:03.607 --> 05:05.653
all the romance
and all the sex

05:05.696 --> 05:07.089
that comes with
making a baby.

05:07.132 --> 05:08.438
Even though we're picking
a sperm donor

05:08.482 --> 05:11.572
from a very unsexy
sperm bank.

05:11.615 --> 05:13.356
Exactly.[ Glass thuds ]

05:13.400 --> 05:16.446
Life has been so hard
and so difficult.

05:18.143 --> 05:20.624
And there's been
so much pain

05:20.668 --> 05:23.497
and so much grief.

05:23.540 --> 05:25.455
I just think we need
a little bit

05:25.499 --> 05:27.327
of something different.

05:27.370 --> 05:30.068
And you need a massage.

05:30.112 --> 05:32.767
Ugh, I really do.

05:32.810 --> 05:34.029
Prego.

05:35.639 --> 05:36.988
Oh.

05:37.032 --> 05:38.294
And I am gonna be

05:38.338 --> 05:41.384
your very sexy
massage therapist today.

05:41.428 --> 05:42.864
[ Laughing ] Oh!

05:42.907 --> 05:46.084
The surprises keep coming.

05:46.128 --> 05:48.260
Carina, this is...

05:48.304 --> 05:49.827
What?

05:49.871 --> 05:51.655
This is so romantic.

05:51.699 --> 05:56.268
♪♪

05:56.312 --> 05:58.619
[ Cellphone ringing ][ Groans ]

06:03.667 --> 06:06.017
What?Oh, that's nice.

06:06.061 --> 06:07.018
Uh, what are you up to?

06:07.062 --> 06:08.803
You wanna --

06:08.846 --> 06:10.195
You wanna come over?

06:11.632 --> 06:12.763
Why?

06:12.807 --> 06:14.722
I don't know.
To hang out.

06:14.765 --> 06:16.201
I'm... [ Sighs ]

06:16.245 --> 06:17.377
Did Andy put you up to this?

06:17.420 --> 06:19.248
No, Travis did.

06:19.291 --> 06:20.684
I don't know --
I think everybody's worried

06:20.728 --> 06:21.511
about the both of us,
and they think we should

06:21.555 --> 06:24.296
babysit each other, so...

06:24.340 --> 06:26.429
I don't know, it's pretty
efficient, honestly.

06:26.473 --> 06:28.126
I can't. I'm -- I'm busy
right now, okay?

06:28.170 --> 06:29.563
Doing what?

06:29.606 --> 06:30.955
Growing a depression beard?

06:30.999 --> 06:32.566
I know you're just
sitting around, miserable,

06:32.609 --> 06:33.697
on the floating Miller shrine.

06:33.741 --> 06:34.959
Hughes.

06:35.003 --> 06:37.179
I have whiskey!

06:37.222 --> 06:39.486
[ Sighs ] Thanks,
but no thanks, okay?

06:43.403 --> 06:44.839
[ Sighs ]

06:44.882 --> 06:46.493
[ Keys jingling ][ Door lock clicks ]

06:50.410 --> 06:51.628
Who are you?

06:51.672 --> 06:53.587
I-I'm Jack Gibson.

06:53.630 --> 06:55.893
W-We've actually met
a lot of times.

06:55.937 --> 06:59.897
Bill, [sighs]
that's Dean's co-worker.

06:59.941 --> 07:01.943
Bill: You can start
in the living room.

07:03.510 --> 07:05.816
I'm gonna -- Okay, yeah.

07:05.860 --> 07:07.470
Sor-- Sorry.
[ Clears throat ]

07:07.514 --> 07:08.732
Why are you here?

07:10.647 --> 07:12.388
Well, uh, Ben --
Ben Warren --

07:12.432 --> 07:14.477
Ben Warren...

07:14.521 --> 07:16.784
is not the owner
of this property.

07:16.827 --> 07:19.439
No, but, um,
in Dean's will --

07:19.482 --> 07:22.093
you know, the -- the house
was going to Pru, and --

07:22.137 --> 07:24.139
Well, we're
Pru's guardians,

07:24.182 --> 07:26.184
and we co-signed the mortgage
on this house.

07:26.228 --> 07:28.056
You should get out.

07:32.539 --> 07:34.584
They've worked out
an arrangement

07:34.628 --> 07:35.977
that all grandparents
seem happy with.

07:36.020 --> 07:37.805
So, they're, what --
gonna ship a child

07:37.848 --> 07:39.371
back and forth
between continents?

07:39.415 --> 07:40.851
No, they have agreed

07:40.895 --> 07:42.636
that Pru will be based
in Seattle.

07:42.679 --> 07:44.159
This will be
her primary residence --

07:44.202 --> 07:46.466
with the Millers --
and she will spend summers

07:46.509 --> 07:47.902
and alternating holidays

07:47.945 --> 07:49.207
with the other set
of grandparents.

07:49.251 --> 07:50.600
In Hong Kong?
No.

07:50.644 --> 07:53.908
They spend their summers
in Italy, apparently.

07:53.951 --> 07:56.650
On a yacht.Oh, my...
[ Scoffs ]

07:56.693 --> 07:59.261
Look -- Okay, look,
Dean stipulated

07:59.304 --> 08:00.523
he wanted her with us.

08:00.567 --> 08:01.742
There are legal documents.

08:01.785 --> 08:02.873
D-D-Doesn't that
mean anything?

08:02.917 --> 08:04.962
Well, it means
everything.Okay.

08:05.006 --> 08:07.922
And it can
also mean nothing.

08:07.965 --> 08:09.401
They have a strong argument
for keeping her.

08:09.445 --> 08:11.969
They are blood relations
who are all more than capable

08:12.013 --> 08:14.363
of supporting her
and raising her

08:14.406 --> 08:17.845
and providing for Pru a life
well beyond the average.

08:17.888 --> 08:20.456
So, if you want to keep her,
it's gonna be a fight.

08:20.500 --> 08:22.240
A long, difficult...

08:22.284 --> 08:24.895
[ Cellphone rings ]...time-consuming,
expensive fight.

08:24.939 --> 08:28.072
If all the adults tasked
with keeping Pru safe

08:28.116 --> 08:29.683
are fighting
with each other,

08:29.726 --> 08:31.075
then who's looking out
for her?

08:31.119 --> 08:32.947
Well, I don't see
an alternative.

08:32.990 --> 08:37.560
The alternative is
we stop thinking about

08:37.604 --> 08:40.258
what Dean wanted
and start thinking about

08:40.302 --> 08:41.782
what's best for Pru.

08:41.825 --> 08:43.697
Weare what's best
for Pru.

08:43.740 --> 08:45.263
So say us!

08:45.307 --> 08:47.570
But if the road to us
is gonna hurt her

08:47.614 --> 08:50.399
in any way, th-- no.

08:50.442 --> 08:51.922
[ Scoffs ] Miranda!

08:51.966 --> 08:53.750
Th-- Th-- Th--
They talk about her

08:53.794 --> 08:55.535
like she's their property.

08:55.578 --> 08:56.666
All right, look --
she, um...

08:56.710 --> 08:59.147
Yeah -- "She belongsto us."

08:59.190 --> 09:00.931
All right?
"She's ourgranddaughter."

09:00.975 --> 09:03.325
A-And you think
we're the ones being selfish?

09:03.368 --> 09:05.762
Dean wanted us
to raise her.

09:05.806 --> 09:07.416
He put it in writing.

09:07.459 --> 09:08.635
[ Cellphone chimes ]

09:10.288 --> 09:11.463
[ Sighing ] Okay.
You know what?

09:11.507 --> 09:12.508
I gotta talk to Gibson.

09:12.552 --> 09:14.989
Just t-tell her
why she's wrong.

09:15.032 --> 09:16.817
[ Sighs ]
Hey, Jack.
What's up?

09:16.860 --> 09:19.602
Look, Dr. Bailey, I still
think in the long run --

09:19.646 --> 09:22.387
The long run won't matter
if we screw her up now,

09:22.431 --> 09:25.782
when her spongy, little brain
is just learning

09:25.826 --> 09:28.002
what the world is like.

09:28.045 --> 09:31.788
Her spongy, little baby brain
is already having to contend

09:31.832 --> 09:36.271
with the fact that her dad,
her adult, her stability,

09:36.314 --> 09:39.709
her protector
is gone, forever.

09:39.753 --> 09:42.669
Now we have to be
the adults for Pru.

09:42.712 --> 09:44.888
We have to
prioritize Pru,

09:44.932 --> 09:48.152
and as much as it pains me
to say this,

09:48.196 --> 09:54.376
if all of this is truly about
protecting that little girl,

09:54.419 --> 09:56.508
then we're standing down.

10:01.426 --> 10:03.385
[ Drill whirring ]

10:03.428 --> 10:05.735
[ Tiles clatters ]Oh, my God.

10:05.779 --> 10:08.129
What did I ever do to you?

10:08.172 --> 10:09.739
[ Sighs ]

10:12.568 --> 10:13.961
Mm.

10:15.745 --> 10:17.704
[ Towel bar clatters ]

10:17.747 --> 10:19.619
Are you kidding me
right now?!

10:21.185 --> 10:22.709
[ Grunting ]

10:26.190 --> 10:27.931
[ Doorbell rings ]

10:27.975 --> 10:29.716
[ Breathing heavily ]

10:29.759 --> 10:31.631
[ Hammer clatters ]

10:36.897 --> 10:38.202
You came.

10:38.246 --> 10:40.378
I see you've stopped
bathing, too.
[ Chuckles ]

10:40.422 --> 10:43.512
"Too" as in you, too,
or "too" like I seem

10:43.555 --> 10:46.254
like I'm ticking off another box
on the list of madness?

10:46.297 --> 10:47.472
Both.
Seriously, smell me.

10:47.516 --> 10:49.474
No.
That's gross, Gibson.Smell me.

10:49.518 --> 10:50.998
I said I had whiskey.

10:51.041 --> 10:54.392
Yeah, but Miller turned me
onto the good stuff and then...

10:54.436 --> 10:55.480
died on me.

10:55.524 --> 10:57.352
Ah, that's rude.

10:57.395 --> 11:00.137
His parents showed up.
Started packing his stuff.

11:00.181 --> 11:01.704
Uh, they're gonna sell
the houseboat.

11:01.748 --> 11:03.140
What?
Yeah.

11:03.184 --> 11:05.577
Couldn't stay to watch,
so I had to get out of there.

11:06.753 --> 11:08.363
What do you know
about tiling?

11:09.538 --> 11:12.280
Come on.

11:12.323 --> 11:13.803
[ Horn blows ]

11:13.847 --> 11:15.892
[ Knock on door ]Travis: Mom?

11:15.936 --> 11:17.154
[ Burt Bacharach's "Always
Something There to Remind Me"
playing on stereo ]

11:17.198 --> 11:18.852
Mom?

11:18.895 --> 11:21.681
Come on, Mom.
I know you're home.

11:21.724 --> 11:24.161
The door was unlocked,
and Burt Bacharach is playing.

11:24.205 --> 11:25.641
♪ When there is always...

11:25.685 --> 11:26.816
Can I help you?

11:26.860 --> 11:28.992
Mom. Hi.

11:29.036 --> 11:30.211
Aw, so nice.

11:30.254 --> 11:32.256
Mom, it's me.
Your only son.

11:32.300 --> 11:35.477
The one you always complain
doesn't visit you enough.

11:35.520 --> 11:37.479
Wait, are you packing?

11:37.522 --> 11:39.176
♪ I was born to love her

11:39.220 --> 11:41.178
Mom, are you
kicking Dad out?

11:41.222 --> 11:42.963
No. I'mleaving.

11:43.006 --> 11:44.181
Do you want this?

11:44.225 --> 11:45.748
Mom. Wait.

11:45.792 --> 11:48.185
Mom, Mom.
Can you just wait one minute?

11:48.229 --> 11:49.360
I can't.

11:49.404 --> 11:51.145
Your father will be home
in a few hours,

11:51.188 --> 11:52.929
and I'd like to be packed
by the time he gets here.

11:52.973 --> 11:54.365
Does Dad not know?

11:54.409 --> 11:55.758
I told him
over breakfast, but...

11:55.802 --> 11:57.760
[chuckles]
...not sure he believed me.

11:57.804 --> 11:59.631
Okay, what did you say
exactly?

11:59.675 --> 12:02.417
I said, "Paul, honey,
I'm leaving."
Okay.

12:02.460 --> 12:03.853
Did you tell him
that apparently

12:03.897 --> 12:05.855
it was something that you
urgently needed to do today?

12:05.899 --> 12:08.205
Your father and I were married
37 years,

12:08.249 --> 12:10.555
and he didn't tell me
he loved men 'til one week ago.

12:10.599 --> 12:12.949
So, yes, it's urgent.

12:12.993 --> 12:15.778
Travis,
either help me pack

12:15.822 --> 12:17.780
or come back
at a more convenient time.

12:21.218 --> 12:23.699
Saw you and Beckett talking
the other day.

12:23.743 --> 12:25.440
[ Sighs ]
It's smart,
getting in with him.

12:25.483 --> 12:27.268
I'd do the same thing.

12:27.311 --> 12:30.227
You prove yourself here,
there's an opening in 19 --

12:30.271 --> 12:31.576
A death at 19.

12:31.620 --> 12:32.926
Well -- Yeah, well,
what I'm saying is that --

12:32.969 --> 12:34.710
Not everything is about
politics, Robert.

12:34.754 --> 12:37.104
[ Klaxon sounds ]Dispatch: Aid car
to 535 Beatrice Court.

12:37.147 --> 12:38.061
Civilian has a burn
from a grease fire.

12:38.105 --> 12:39.280
Politics?
That's you.

12:39.323 --> 12:41.108
I know that's me.Ruiz, go with Sullivan.

12:41.151 --> 12:43.545
Maddox,
you're on engine.I know.

12:43.588 --> 12:45.329
It's hard to believe
that I've done this before.

12:45.373 --> 12:47.114
Maddox, you ever eat
a vegetable?

12:47.157 --> 12:49.377
Some fruit maybe?
Food with food in it?

12:49.420 --> 12:51.771
You know, these are, in fact,
loops of fruit, so...
Got it.

12:51.814 --> 12:53.773
Well, if you don't put
nutrients in your body,

12:53.816 --> 12:54.948
you're gonna have a hard time
with all the drills

12:54.991 --> 12:56.427
I make you run later.Oh, my God.

12:56.471 --> 12:58.995
You are so preoccupied
with my body, it is crazy.

12:59.039 --> 13:00.867
Hey, probie, will you dump this
for me, please?

13:04.566 --> 13:06.350
Maddox, go easy
on Duval.

13:06.394 --> 13:07.525
What, you don't
haze probies at 19?

13:07.569 --> 13:08.788
Not like that.

13:08.831 --> 13:10.354
Okay.
[ Chuckles ]

13:10.398 --> 13:12.574
[ Sighs ]

13:12.617 --> 13:15.403
Become a captain,
they said.

13:15.446 --> 13:18.058
It'll be rewarding, they said.
[ Chuckles ]

13:18.101 --> 13:18.841
[ Siren wails ]

13:24.325 --> 13:25.587
Jack:
Alright, one, two --

13:25.630 --> 13:27.850
Wait. Wait.

13:27.894 --> 13:29.852
Are you sure you turned off
the water?

13:29.896 --> 13:31.375
Yes.

13:31.419 --> 13:32.333
Question mark.
Yeah.

13:32.376 --> 13:34.161
Mm.
Yeah, no.

13:34.204 --> 13:36.467
[ Sighs ]

13:36.511 --> 13:38.252
You know, I'm kinda glad
I'm getting kicked out
of the houseboat.

13:38.295 --> 13:40.036
I feel like he's always
about to round the corner

13:40.080 --> 13:41.472
when I'm there.

13:41.516 --> 13:43.474
And the way I hear
his jazz records.

13:43.518 --> 13:47.435
I smell his stupid good lasagna
that we begged him to make.

13:47.478 --> 13:49.219
And he taught me
what beshmall sauce was.

13:49.263 --> 13:51.874
What sauce?

13:51.918 --> 13:54.050
Beshmall.

13:54.094 --> 13:56.444
Okay, so he taught you
how to make béchamel sauce,

13:56.487 --> 13:57.880
but not how to say it?

13:57.924 --> 14:00.665
That...sounds like Miller.
[ Laughs ]

14:00.709 --> 14:02.711
Whatever.

14:02.754 --> 14:05.279
I thought living there
would keep him close,

14:05.322 --> 14:07.411
but it kinda just
makes it worse.

14:08.369 --> 14:10.937
[ Laughs ]

14:10.980 --> 14:13.374
I'm --
Am I funny? What --No, I just --

14:13.417 --> 14:16.768
I can't help just picturing
Miller as this, like,

14:16.812 --> 14:19.902
jazz-cat-lasagna-ghost,
and it's just --

14:19.946 --> 14:21.904
It's pretty great.
It's pretty great.

14:21.948 --> 14:24.341
[ Both chuckling ]

14:24.385 --> 14:25.821
Yeah.

14:25.865 --> 14:27.170
Honestly, I-I don't know
how you do it.

14:27.214 --> 14:29.607
How...

14:29.651 --> 14:32.175
How you live
on the houseboat.

14:32.219 --> 14:35.396
Feels like he's everywhere
in this house,

14:35.439 --> 14:37.354
and he was barely
ever here.

14:37.398 --> 14:38.790
[ Grunts ]Whoa!

14:38.834 --> 14:41.750
Hughes! Come on!

14:41.793 --> 14:44.100
Oh, come on.
What was the agreement, Gibson?

14:44.144 --> 14:47.103
No questioning the other
person's actions today.

14:47.147 --> 14:48.452
Yeah.

14:48.496 --> 14:49.889
Come on.

14:49.932 --> 14:51.325
Come on.

14:51.368 --> 14:52.761
Yeah, give me that.

14:52.804 --> 14:54.806
[ Breathing heavily ]

14:59.768 --> 15:00.943
[ Chuckles ]

15:00.987 --> 15:02.510
Whew.

15:02.553 --> 15:04.599
Feel good?
Yeah.
Feels good.

15:04.642 --> 15:06.079
Yeah?
Feels good.

15:06.122 --> 15:08.211
I mean, maybe not the normal way
to work through grief,

15:08.255 --> 15:09.560
but, yeah, okay.

15:09.604 --> 15:10.518
There is nothing normal
about this.

15:10.561 --> 15:11.998
Oh. Okay.

15:12.041 --> 15:13.869
[ Breathing heavily ]

15:13.913 --> 15:15.871
Yeah.
We lost one
of our people!

15:15.915 --> 15:19.092
The fate of a little girl
hangs in the balance!

15:19.135 --> 15:21.703
And I have a literal
broken heart!

15:21.746 --> 15:24.706
[ Heart monitor beeping ]

15:24.749 --> 15:26.316
Get the whiskey.Yeah. Whiskey.

15:26.360 --> 15:27.317
Yeah.Mm-hmm.
Here we go.

15:27.361 --> 15:28.101
Gah![ Tile clattering ]

15:28.144 --> 15:29.841
[ Grunting ]

15:32.366 --> 15:34.194
[ Breathing heavily ]

15:36.283 --> 15:37.849
Mm.
Number two --

15:37.893 --> 15:39.851
[smooches]
...this freckle.

15:39.895 --> 15:42.202
It's a beauty mark.

15:42.245 --> 15:44.856
And we're counting blessings,
not body parts.

15:44.900 --> 15:48.643
Well, I am feeling very blessed
by your body parts.

15:48.686 --> 15:50.253
Number three.

15:50.297 --> 15:52.255
Mm.
A healthy body.

15:52.299 --> 15:53.648
See?
[ Giggles ]

15:53.691 --> 15:54.910
Number four.
Mm.

15:54.954 --> 15:56.390
You turning
what could have been

15:56.433 --> 15:58.435
a day full of grief
and housekeeping

15:58.479 --> 16:01.221
into the most romantic day
of my life.

16:01.264 --> 16:03.005
Aside from our wedding.

16:03.049 --> 16:04.702
Well, that one got
a little dinged

16:04.746 --> 16:06.878
by the whole
losing-my-job thing.

16:06.922 --> 16:08.445
Mm. Right.

16:08.489 --> 16:10.665
Okay, number five.

16:10.708 --> 16:11.971
Mm.

16:14.712 --> 16:16.584
Multiple orgasms.Mm.

16:21.110 --> 16:22.938
[ Dog barking, children playing
in distance ]

16:25.027 --> 16:27.987
It's not that he's gay,
you know.

16:28.030 --> 16:28.988
I know.

16:29.031 --> 16:30.990
I need you to know that.

16:31.033 --> 16:33.166
I never had a problem
with your being gay.

16:33.209 --> 16:34.689
Right.

16:34.732 --> 16:37.431
You just let Dad's internalized
homophobia prevent you

16:37.474 --> 16:39.824
from fully accepting me.

16:39.868 --> 16:41.217
I accepted you.

16:41.261 --> 16:42.262
Yeah, right, Mom.

16:42.305 --> 16:43.698
You didn't even come
to my wedding.

16:46.092 --> 16:48.920
Travis, you know why.

16:48.964 --> 16:51.793
It was just easier to go along
with what he wanted

16:51.836 --> 16:54.361
than to...

16:54.404 --> 16:56.189
He took my whole life.

16:56.232 --> 16:58.756
My relationship
with my son.

17:04.632 --> 17:07.069
Dad was drowning in shame
and self-loathing,

17:07.113 --> 17:09.071
so he did
a lot of things wrong,

17:09.115 --> 17:11.073
but he never put a gun
to your head.

17:11.117 --> 17:13.032
You chose not to come
to my wedding.

17:13.075 --> 17:16.513
And we can be as mad at him
as we want to be.

17:16.557 --> 17:19.125
But we can't
put that on him.

17:19.168 --> 17:22.519
He told you not to go,
and you went along with that.

17:22.563 --> 17:24.478
So, that's on you.

17:24.521 --> 17:27.046
Do you think I don't regret
not being at your wedding?

17:29.178 --> 17:33.095
Not being there to read my poem
for you and Michael?

17:33.139 --> 17:35.880
I've always let things be,
let things lie.

17:35.924 --> 17:37.099
I know you have, Mom.

17:37.143 --> 17:39.362
And so I'm saying
that's on you.

17:41.582 --> 17:43.105
Do you want some lunch?

17:43.149 --> 17:45.325
I can heat up
some chap chae.

17:47.762 --> 17:50.069
[ Sirens wailing ]

17:50.112 --> 17:52.984
Grease fire burn.
Shouldn't take long.

17:53.028 --> 17:54.551
Hey, how's Hughes?

17:54.595 --> 17:57.293
She's healing,
and she's grieving,

17:57.337 --> 18:00.514
and she's impatient about how
long both things are taking.

18:00.557 --> 18:02.124
Yep.
Sounds about right.

18:02.168 --> 18:04.126
You know, when I started,
I received some advice,

18:04.170 --> 18:05.954
which I ignored --

18:05.997 --> 18:07.782
never marry another
firefighter.
[ Chuckles ]

18:07.825 --> 18:10.001
Whoa.
I'm not getting married.

18:10.045 --> 18:12.613
No, I know.
I changed the subject to me.

18:12.656 --> 18:14.397
Got it.
I just...

18:14.441 --> 18:15.659
I don't get it.

18:15.703 --> 18:18.097
I just don't get
how I ended up here.

18:18.140 --> 18:22.057
Subbing as a grunt in my
soon-to-be-ex-wife's house.

18:22.101 --> 18:24.146
You really think
it's about the job?

18:24.190 --> 18:27.193
I mean, with a firefighter,
at least we get each other.

18:27.236 --> 18:29.195
No, that's the problem.

18:29.238 --> 18:31.022
See, this is not
a normal job.

18:31.066 --> 18:32.589
There's too much loss.

18:32.633 --> 18:33.808
There's too much pain.

18:33.851 --> 18:35.853
There's too much trauma.

18:35.897 --> 18:38.639
We need to be able to put it all
away when we get home.

18:38.682 --> 18:40.858
We need to be able
to come home to somebody

18:40.902 --> 18:43.644
who does not get it.

18:43.687 --> 18:45.167
Tell me I'm wrong.

18:45.211 --> 18:47.169
Tell me that when you see
Hughes suffering

18:47.213 --> 18:48.866
because her
best friend died,

18:48.910 --> 18:51.260
that you don't think about
everyone you've lost.

19:05.361 --> 19:15.284
♪♪

19:15.328 --> 19:17.721
Oh!

19:17.765 --> 19:19.332
Dispatch from Aid 23.

19:19.375 --> 19:21.551
Smoke and fire from a unit
on the third floor.

19:21.595 --> 19:23.771
Send full structure assignment.

19:23.814 --> 19:26.339
Yeah, this is more than
a grease fire burn.

19:26.382 --> 19:29.298
[ Dramatic music plays ]

19:29.342 --> 19:31.300
I mean, how can they sell
his house?

19:31.344 --> 19:32.910
Did they pay for it?

19:32.954 --> 19:34.695
Well, I think they co-signed
and paid the down payment.

19:34.738 --> 19:36.000
Then it's theirs
to sell.

19:37.915 --> 19:39.830
I'm sure they'll put the money
in a trust for her.

19:39.874 --> 19:41.963
It's not like
they're hard up for cash.

19:43.747 --> 19:47.055
How -- How did you suddenly get
this...cold?

19:47.098 --> 19:49.710
Okay, do not
for a second think

19:49.753 --> 19:52.103
that my heart isn't every bit
as broken as yours.

19:52.147 --> 19:53.801
Well, it's not the time
to be heartbroken.

19:53.844 --> 19:55.019
Alright?
It's the time to fight.

19:55.063 --> 19:56.804
Ben, look,
it's not right, okay?

19:56.847 --> 19:59.241
Ripping that child
from her grandparents,

19:59.285 --> 20:00.286
fighting over property.

20:00.329 --> 20:02.505
This cannot be us.

20:02.549 --> 20:04.290
This cannot be
what Miller wanted.

20:04.333 --> 20:05.813
No. No, no.

20:05.856 --> 20:08.032
What Miller wanted was for her
to be with us, alright?

20:08.076 --> 20:10.034
And for her to grow up with
that place, you know,

20:10.078 --> 20:11.775
to know where her dad
was his happiest,

20:11.819 --> 20:13.821
where her dad became a man,
where --

20:13.864 --> 20:15.562
where her dad
set in motion plans

20:15.605 --> 20:18.173
not -- not just for her future,
but for the world.

20:18.217 --> 20:19.566
Okay, no.
No, no, no.

20:19.609 --> 20:20.741
Don't -- Don't look at me
like that.

20:20.784 --> 20:22.133
I'm not being
sentimental.

20:22.177 --> 20:24.701
Don't you see
what they're doing?

20:24.745 --> 20:26.703
Dean's parents don't care
about what Dean wanted,

20:26.747 --> 20:30.011
because Dean's parents never
cared about what he wanted.

20:30.054 --> 20:33.928
They only wanted to control him,
to -- to squeeze out

20:33.971 --> 20:36.278
every part of him that
they didn't approve of.

20:36.322 --> 20:39.673
Dean -- Dean hated that,

20:39.716 --> 20:44.765
which is why he wanted
his daughter to be raised by us.

20:48.203 --> 20:49.813
Ben...

20:49.857 --> 20:52.207
Miranda, you -- you are normally
right about everything,

20:52.251 --> 20:54.383
but you are not right
about this, alright?

20:54.427 --> 20:56.646
You are not right
about this.

20:59.954 --> 21:01.782
Okay.

21:04.001 --> 21:05.873
Okay?

21:05.916 --> 21:07.527
You're right.

21:09.268 --> 21:13.750
[ Exhales sharply ]
So -- So, we're gonna fight?

21:16.449 --> 21:18.146
We're gonna fight
for her?

21:18.189 --> 21:19.539
We're gonna fight.

21:19.582 --> 21:21.236
[ Laughs ]
Yeah, we are.

21:21.280 --> 21:22.411
Ohh!

21:22.455 --> 21:23.891
Okay.

21:25.458 --> 21:26.459
[ Sighs ]

21:29.375 --> 21:32.769
[ Siren wails ]

21:32.813 --> 21:33.944
Sullivan:
Watch your step.

21:33.988 --> 21:35.642
You're gonna walk
straight out.

21:36.382 --> 21:38.166
Sullivan, status?

21:38.209 --> 21:39.950
We responded
to a grease fire burn

21:39.994 --> 21:41.648
and saw the smoke
from that window,

21:41.691 --> 21:43.650
but the reporting party's
not answering the door.

21:43.693 --> 21:44.825
Where's Ruiz?He's on the third floor.

21:44.868 --> 21:46.348
He's not in gear.
We started evac.

21:46.392 --> 21:48.002
He's trying to get inside
to the patient with the burn.

21:48.045 --> 21:49.220
Alright,
you're on fire attack.

21:49.264 --> 21:50.178
Get in there
with the battering ram.

21:50.221 --> 21:51.614
Go, go, go.

21:51.658 --> 21:52.876
Duval, Maddox,
you're on evac.

21:52.920 --> 21:54.661
Get everyone else
off the third floor.

21:54.704 --> 21:57.054
Engine 23,
load the dry standpipes.

21:57.098 --> 21:59.361
Ruiz, I need you down here
on the ground right now.

21:59.405 --> 22:01.015
[ Coughing ]

22:01.058 --> 22:02.886
[ Radio beeps ]Someone's in here, Cap.

22:02.930 --> 22:04.584
Please. It's Naomi.
She's our friend.

22:04.627 --> 22:06.890
Andy:
Sullivan's on his way.
You're not in gear.

22:06.934 --> 22:08.501
Copy. Come on.
We gotta get you outside.

22:08.544 --> 22:09.893
Wait,
no, no, no, no.

22:09.937 --> 22:10.981
You're just gonna leave her
in there?

22:11.025 --> 22:12.026
No, someone's coming up
right now.

22:12.069 --> 22:12.766
No, no, no,
we're not leaving her.

22:12.809 --> 22:13.984
She's in a wheelchair.

22:14.028 --> 22:15.812
Maddox: Hurry up, Duval.
Stay with me.

22:15.856 --> 22:17.684
Hey, aren't we supposed to be
clearing the third floor?

22:17.727 --> 22:20.687
Ah, evac's for losers.
Fire attack's where it's at.

22:20.730 --> 22:22.428
[ Banging on door ]Seattle Fire!
Let's go!

22:22.471 --> 22:23.864
Maddox, you're on evac.

22:23.907 --> 22:25.431
Sullivan's on his way up.
He and I have this.

22:25.474 --> 22:27.998
Oh, I coulda sworn Herrera just
told you to go outside.

22:28.042 --> 22:29.565
Maddox, you have
two seconds to move.

22:29.609 --> 22:31.393
Come on.
Let's go.

22:31.437 --> 22:34.396
[ Radio beeps ]Captain, civilian's
in a wheelchair.

22:34.440 --> 22:36.224
Copy that, Ruiz.
Sullivan's on his way up.

22:36.267 --> 22:38.139
Get down here and suit up.

22:38.182 --> 22:41.708
♪♪

22:41.751 --> 22:43.362
[ Knocking ]

22:46.365 --> 22:47.931
Oh. Hi.

22:47.975 --> 22:50.499
My granddaughter
is not here.

22:50.543 --> 22:52.719
She's with her aunt.

22:52.762 --> 22:54.111
My daughter.

22:54.155 --> 22:55.722
Her family.

22:55.765 --> 22:57.332
Th-That's good.
That's fine.

22:57.376 --> 22:58.986
We, uh --
We came here, actually,

22:59.029 --> 23:00.988
because we wanted
to speak with you.

23:01.031 --> 23:04.992
Yes, we -- we don't want
to fight with you, with lawyers.

23:05.035 --> 23:10.650
Um, we want peace, for you,
for ourselves, for Pru.

23:10.693 --> 23:14.697
We are hoping that we can,
you know, talk it out

23:14.741 --> 23:17.178
and -- and come
to an agreement.

23:17.221 --> 23:19.485
I understand this must be
difficult for both of you

23:19.528 --> 23:21.922
because you want to honor
my son's wishes.

23:21.965 --> 23:25.186
But in this case, he's simply
incorrect in the matter.

23:25.229 --> 23:28.581
And as his mother,
I've had to overrule him.

23:28.624 --> 23:31.584
Your son was
an adult,

23:31.627 --> 23:35.196
and he made verbal and legally
documented decisions

23:35.239 --> 23:36.632
for his daughter.

23:36.676 --> 23:38.634
My son made a lot of decisions
in his life

23:38.678 --> 23:41.245
that I would have overruled,
had I had the opportunity.

23:41.289 --> 23:43.291
If he'd listened to us about
his choice of profession,

23:43.334 --> 23:44.858
well, we wouldn't be
in this position,

23:44.901 --> 23:46.468
because he'd still
be alive.

23:46.512 --> 23:49.515
With all due respect, um,
I know you're in pain,

23:49.558 --> 23:52.126
but I don't think
you're being fair.

23:52.169 --> 23:53.475
You don't have to think
it's "fair."

23:53.519 --> 23:55.216
It's the truth.

23:59.394 --> 24:00.656
How do you let him
do it?

24:00.700 --> 24:02.745
S--
I'm -- I'm sorry?

24:02.789 --> 24:07.663
How do you let your husband,
who's a trained surgeon,

24:07.707 --> 24:12.059
jeopardize his life every day
and call it a career?

24:12.102 --> 24:14.975
I'm not in charge
of Ben's decision-making

24:15.018 --> 24:17.934
a-any more than you were
in charge of Dean's.

24:17.978 --> 24:21.372
Don't you think a husband
should have enough respect

24:21.416 --> 24:23.418
for his wife and children

24:23.462 --> 24:27.814
to prioritize his own life
over the lives of strangers?

24:27.857 --> 24:29.250
Okay, that's enough.

24:29.293 --> 24:30.294
Oh!

24:30.338 --> 24:32.035
You march onto my property,

24:32.079 --> 24:34.690
you start making demands, and
you tell mewhen it's enough?

24:34.734 --> 24:36.736
Ben --But you don't have the right
to speak to my wife that way.

24:36.779 --> 24:38.955
Ben, I'm capable
of speaking for myself.

24:38.999 --> 24:43.220
My husband is a brave
and noble man.

24:43.264 --> 24:48.312
He is a hero who saves lives
every day, as was your son.

24:48.356 --> 24:51.664
He does a job that very few
are brave enough to do, and --

24:51.707 --> 24:54.057
and that doesn't make him
less of a husband,

24:54.101 --> 24:56.538
and it doesn't make him
any less a father.

24:56.582 --> 24:58.453
[ Seagulls crying in distance ]

25:01.587 --> 25:04.241
Maybe it doesn't.

25:04.285 --> 25:06.243
But it does make him a man
who's likely to be dead

25:06.287 --> 25:07.593
before his time.

25:07.636 --> 25:09.682
How dare you?
How --

25:09.725 --> 25:11.118
How dare I?

25:11.161 --> 25:13.294
How dare you?

25:13.337 --> 25:16.471
You want me to hand
my only grandchild over to you

25:16.515 --> 25:20.519
so she can lose and bury
yet another father?

25:20.562 --> 25:24.261
You want her to suffer more
than she already has?

25:24.305 --> 25:26.220
How dare you?

25:26.263 --> 25:32.487
♪♪

25:32.531 --> 25:35.229
Look, our son just died.
Our beautiful son.

25:35.272 --> 25:37.492
Our only son.

25:37.536 --> 25:39.059
Look,
you are both parents.

25:39.102 --> 25:42.671
Can you imagine for a moment
how that feels?

25:42.715 --> 25:44.630
And now you want to take
more from us?

25:44.673 --> 25:47.241
Any of us
can raise a child.

25:47.284 --> 25:49.548
But Miranda and I are
the only ones able to do it

25:49.591 --> 25:51.898
and honor Dean
in that process.

25:51.941 --> 25:54.117
To teach her about
all the incredible parts

25:54.161 --> 25:55.684
of -- of her father

25:55.728 --> 25:58.644
that he could never show you
because you hated what he did.

25:58.687 --> 26:02.082
You -- You couldn't honor Dean
and what he wanted in his life.

26:02.125 --> 26:04.737
[ Banging on counter ]Please, please honor
what he wanted in his death.

26:06.782 --> 26:08.784
We are her family.

26:08.828 --> 26:12.179
Yes, and we would never
take her from you.

26:12.222 --> 26:15.922
You -- You can have as much
access to her as you like.

26:15.965 --> 26:17.750
Well, how gracious of you

26:17.793 --> 26:20.274
to offer us "access"
to our grandchild.

26:21.623 --> 26:23.364
That's enough now.

26:23.407 --> 26:33.287
♪♪

26:38.335 --> 26:39.598
Hey, did they get
Naomi out?

26:39.641 --> 26:41.600
They're working on it.
She's gonna be okay.

26:41.643 --> 26:43.993
Deja: Okay, guys, follow me.
Over here. This direction.

26:44.037 --> 26:45.255
Where's Maddox?

26:45.299 --> 26:46.692
He said he wanted to be
"where the action is."

26:46.735 --> 26:48.215
What?

26:48.258 --> 26:49.651
I just followed your orders.
I --

26:49.695 --> 26:51.479
Maddox, you abandoned
your partner.

26:51.522 --> 26:52.828
Get down here, now.

26:52.872 --> 26:54.264
Good work, Duval.

26:54.308 --> 26:56.179
Ruiz! You're on fire attack
with Sullivan.

26:56.223 --> 26:58.834
Yeah.

26:58.878 --> 26:59.835
[ Alarm blaring ]

26:59.879 --> 27:01.532
Sullivan: Here we go.
Alright.

27:01.576 --> 27:02.533
Got it?

27:02.577 --> 27:03.578
Alright, let's go.

27:03.622 --> 27:04.797
Yep! Whoo!

27:04.840 --> 27:06.276
Alright.
Yippie-kai-ay!

27:06.320 --> 27:08.670
[ Grunts ]Maddox, Captain said
you're out!

27:08.714 --> 27:10.324
Now!Hey, hey, hey, hey!

27:10.367 --> 27:11.586
Female firefighter:
Anyone in there? Let's go!

27:11.630 --> 27:12.848
Alright, alright.
You ready?

27:12.892 --> 27:14.502
Theo: Yeah.
Go, go, go!

27:14.545 --> 27:16.243
[ Grunts ]

27:16.286 --> 27:18.419
[ Indistinct shouting ]

27:18.462 --> 27:24.120
♪♪

27:24.164 --> 27:26.296
Stay low.
Work toward the left.

27:26.340 --> 27:27.733
Naomi!

27:27.776 --> 27:30.300
We got heavy smoke.
We need blowers.

27:30.344 --> 27:31.737
Naomi!

27:33.347 --> 27:34.827
I found her!

27:38.874 --> 27:40.528
I got her!

27:42.399 --> 27:45.185
On three.
One, two, three.

27:45.228 --> 27:51.191
♪♪

27:51.234 --> 27:54.150
She's still breathing.

27:54.194 --> 27:55.586
On three.
Ready.

27:55.630 --> 27:56.762
One, two...

27:56.805 --> 27:58.154
Three!

28:01.592 --> 28:02.942
Maddox,
are you kidding me?

28:02.985 --> 28:05.988
Yippie-kai-ay,
Lieutenant!

28:06.032 --> 28:08.817
[ Indistinct shouting ]

28:08.861 --> 28:10.601
[ Water spraying ]

28:10.645 --> 28:12.168
Whoo!

28:14.605 --> 28:15.955
Mm. Mm. Mm.

28:15.998 --> 28:16.956
[ Snapping fingers ]

28:16.999 --> 28:19.001
We missed a tile.

28:19.045 --> 28:20.176
Get it. Get it.
Get it.

28:20.220 --> 28:22.352
Yeah!
[ Laughs ]

28:22.396 --> 28:23.963
[ Chuckles ]

28:24.006 --> 28:26.008
Hey, if you wanted
perfect,

28:26.052 --> 28:28.445
you should not
have gotten us drunk.

28:28.489 --> 28:30.360
Mm, I think Miller would
probably be proud of me

28:30.404 --> 28:32.145
for not just moping around,
at least.

28:32.188 --> 28:33.755
You know, he'd be
proud of me, too,

28:33.799 --> 28:37.324
for not picking up the first
girl at a bar to sleep with.

28:37.367 --> 28:39.282
It's first impulse

28:39.326 --> 28:41.023
when I'm feeling feelings
I don't wanna feel.

28:41.067 --> 28:42.459
No, I get it!
I get it. I get it.

28:42.503 --> 28:44.244
Sex is, like, the only time
my brain can turn off.

28:44.287 --> 28:46.028
Same. Yes.

28:46.072 --> 28:48.248
Same.
Even after Ripley.

28:48.291 --> 28:50.206
Everyone just thought
I was rebounding,

28:50.250 --> 28:53.514
and I just needed to, like --
I just needed to turn it off.

28:53.557 --> 28:56.473
I get that, because, you know,
this job sucks sometimes,

28:56.517 --> 29:00.782
and there's only so many ways
that you can feel less pain.

29:02.349 --> 29:04.873
How long did you know that
Miller was in love with me?

29:04.917 --> 29:07.397
[ Clears throat ]

29:07.441 --> 29:08.921
That long?
What, like a year?

29:10.836 --> 29:12.402
Aw, shut up, Gibson.
More than a year?

29:12.446 --> 29:14.404
Hey. Hey!

29:14.448 --> 29:16.058
Ugh!
He was scared

29:16.102 --> 29:19.235
that if he told you,
it'd ruin the friendship.

29:19.279 --> 29:22.586
Because he didn't think
you felt the same way.

29:22.630 --> 29:24.414
Well, he was right.

29:24.458 --> 29:27.026
Still would've liked to have had
the conversation, though.

29:28.636 --> 29:30.551
So, what's our
whiskey sitch, huh?

29:30.594 --> 29:31.987
God.

29:32.031 --> 29:33.249
[ Grunts ]

29:36.122 --> 29:37.514
This is a disaster.

29:37.558 --> 29:39.952
Yeah, Montgomery's gonna
murder me.

29:39.995 --> 29:41.431
[ Hammer pounds ]

29:43.259 --> 29:44.434
Carina:
You said that.

29:44.478 --> 29:46.393
Mm.
I did not say that!

29:46.436 --> 29:48.395
You did!
I did not.

29:48.438 --> 29:50.049
You did!

29:50.092 --> 29:52.007
And you did it
that Maya way.

29:52.051 --> 29:54.183
Maya way?
What way is that?

29:54.227 --> 29:56.795
The way you get, mm,
when things are not in order.

29:56.838 --> 29:58.709
You get all stiff,

29:58.753 --> 30:01.712
like you're trying to control
every muscle in your body.

30:01.756 --> 30:03.279
What?
I make that face?

30:03.323 --> 30:05.847
Oh, yes.
The face is the best part.

30:05.891 --> 30:08.284
I'm Maya Bishop.

30:08.328 --> 30:10.069
Oh, my God.
[ Chuckles ]

30:10.112 --> 30:12.680
I'm gonna be the strict mom,
aren't I?

30:12.723 --> 30:14.900
[ Laughing ] Yeah.

30:18.164 --> 30:21.558
You know, I've spent
my whole adult life

30:21.602 --> 30:23.169
bringing babies
into the world

30:23.212 --> 30:25.345
and then watching them
getting rolled away.

30:25.388 --> 30:27.347
I never get to see
how they turn out,

30:27.390 --> 30:29.915
or -- or what kind of mothers
my patients will be.

30:29.958 --> 30:32.439
I just -- I just --

30:32.482 --> 30:35.442
"Welcome, little one.
Bye-bye. Have a nice life."

30:35.485 --> 30:37.313
You want to be
the one who carries.

30:38.575 --> 30:40.142
Eh, we can talk
about that.

30:40.186 --> 30:42.362
I know you're an athlete and you
might want to experience --

30:42.405 --> 30:43.842
No, it's you.

30:45.539 --> 30:46.888
And for the egg?

30:46.932 --> 30:48.107
We can do IVF --

30:48.150 --> 30:50.152
Nope.
It should be yours.

30:52.111 --> 30:54.287
I want to hold
a little you.

30:54.330 --> 30:57.856
I want them to have these eyes
and this nose.

30:57.899 --> 30:59.248
[ Giggles ]

30:59.292 --> 31:01.947
And this freckle.

31:01.990 --> 31:03.339
I want to have
another version of you

31:03.383 --> 31:05.341
that I can count
my blessings on.

31:05.385 --> 31:13.001
♪♪

31:13.045 --> 31:16.004
And I have some ideas

31:16.048 --> 31:18.920
of some places to put
this chocolate sauce.

31:18.964 --> 31:20.748
I told you --
we're making a porn.

31:20.791 --> 31:22.576
No, Maya! No!

31:22.619 --> 31:23.925
Uh, a little bit.

31:23.969 --> 31:25.884
Sullivan:
Alright, here we go.

31:25.927 --> 31:27.059
Good job, Ruiz.

31:27.102 --> 31:29.191
Yeah, same, man.
Same.

31:29.235 --> 31:32.673
-Good work. Good work.
-Bad boys!

31:32.716 --> 31:33.761
[ Grunts ]Good job
out there, man.

31:33.804 --> 31:35.241
Andy: Maddox!

31:35.284 --> 31:36.851
Did I say you were
on fire attack?

31:36.895 --> 31:38.592
No, you didn't,
but you know what?

31:38.635 --> 31:39.941
Not everybody's born
a leader.

31:39.985 --> 31:42.030
Ooh!
[ Laughs ]

31:45.207 --> 31:47.906
They would have listened to you,
if you were acting captain.

31:47.949 --> 31:49.081
Stop.

31:53.128 --> 31:54.956
You get along
with Sullivan, huh?

31:55.000 --> 31:56.784
Eh, he's a hell of
a firefighter.

31:56.827 --> 31:59.482
Yeah, must be nice
to just waltz into any
station and get respect.

31:59.526 --> 32:00.744
Nope.

32:00.788 --> 32:02.094
No.
You're captain.

32:02.137 --> 32:04.139
You can't bring that
personal crap to the team.

32:04.183 --> 32:05.924
Sullivan and I worked
well together.

32:05.967 --> 32:07.099
I respect him.

32:07.142 --> 32:09.231
That's a good thing.
For your team.

32:09.275 --> 32:10.711
They'll never listen to me.

32:10.754 --> 32:12.147
Make them.

32:17.500 --> 32:18.893
I was weak.

32:21.026 --> 32:22.679
I have no excuse.

32:24.464 --> 32:26.640
I was weak.

32:26.683 --> 32:29.425
And you deserved better.

32:29.469 --> 32:31.732
You were a delight.

32:33.473 --> 32:36.302
And your father was
so hard on you.

32:36.345 --> 32:39.914
Not just after you came out,
but your whole childhood.

32:39.958 --> 32:41.002
[ Refrigerator door closes ]

32:41.046 --> 32:43.570
He was so tough on you,

32:43.613 --> 32:48.749
always telling you you were
too sensitive or too emotional.

32:48.792 --> 32:51.665
Trying to toughen you up
by being rough with you,

32:51.708 --> 32:54.973
as if he were afraid
of how you might turn out.

32:57.453 --> 32:59.194
And I hated it.

33:04.634 --> 33:06.854
And I let him.

33:06.897 --> 33:09.552
I let him.

33:09.596 --> 33:13.556
I am so angry
with your father.

33:13.600 --> 33:17.343
[ Voice breaking ]
And I am so angry with myself.

33:17.386 --> 33:22.435
You were never anything
but perfect, Travis.

33:22.478 --> 33:29.224
♪♪

33:29.268 --> 33:35.796
♪♪

33:35.839 --> 33:37.450
[ Chuckles ]

33:37.493 --> 33:39.800
I think it might be time
to call a professional.

33:39.843 --> 33:43.847
[ Chuckles ]

33:43.891 --> 33:45.458
[ Grunts ]
No, Gibson!

33:45.501 --> 33:47.242
Gibson!
Gibson, stop!

33:47.286 --> 33:48.896
[ Grunting ]

33:48.939 --> 33:57.687
♪♪

33:57.731 --> 34:02.910
♪ Too far a way to go

34:02.953 --> 34:07.088
♪ Can't see the light

34:07.132 --> 34:09.482
Jack.

34:09.525 --> 34:11.092
[ Hammer clatters ]

34:11.136 --> 34:13.051
[ Breathing shakily ]

34:15.140 --> 34:16.750
[ Sobbing ]

34:16.793 --> 34:20.754
♪ Into your

34:20.797 --> 34:24.279
♪ Into your heart

34:24.323 --> 34:26.629
Jack. Jack.

34:26.673 --> 34:28.849
[ Sobbing ]

34:31.156 --> 34:33.158
♪ Ooh, ooh

34:33.201 --> 34:35.638
Why can't I stop
feeling this way?

34:35.682 --> 34:37.336
♪ Ooh, ooh

34:37.379 --> 34:40.339
I don't know.

34:40.382 --> 34:43.211
It's okay.
It's okay.

34:43.255 --> 34:45.387
[ Sobbing ]

34:45.431 --> 34:51.001
♪♪

34:51.045 --> 34:56.529
♪♪

34:56.572 --> 34:57.965
[ Music stops ]

35:05.059 --> 35:06.452
[ Both gasping ]

35:10.456 --> 35:11.805
[ Jack clears throat ]

35:11.848 --> 35:13.589
[ Crying ]

35:13.633 --> 35:21.815
♪♪

35:21.858 --> 35:24.122
I should, um --
Yeah. Yeah.

35:24.165 --> 35:25.862
You didn't --
You didn't drive, right?

35:28.169 --> 35:29.910
Y-Yeah, Gibson,
just don't.

35:29.953 --> 35:32.956
[ Clears throat ]

35:33.000 --> 35:35.698
♪ Make me out a fool

35:35.742 --> 35:39.833
♪♪

35:39.876 --> 35:43.402
[ Breathing shakily ]

35:43.445 --> 35:45.534
[ Sobbing ]

35:45.578 --> 35:53.281
♪♪

35:53.325 --> 36:01.159
♪♪

36:05.598 --> 36:07.556
[ Siren wailing in distance ]

36:17.044 --> 36:18.959
[ Exhales sharply ]

36:21.614 --> 36:23.268
Listen up!

36:25.835 --> 36:27.663
Let me help you understand.

36:27.707 --> 36:30.231
I am not your
substitute teacher.

36:30.275 --> 36:32.233
I am your captain.

36:32.277 --> 36:34.931
In the house, on calls,
in the field,

36:34.975 --> 36:37.325
you answer
and take orders from me.

36:37.369 --> 36:40.328
When you disobey my orders,
you put your team at risk.

36:40.372 --> 36:41.938
When you leave your partner
during a fire,

36:41.982 --> 36:43.766
you put your team at risk.

36:43.810 --> 36:47.814
If either of those things happen
again, you put your job at risk.

36:50.860 --> 36:53.080
I'm not done, Maddox.

36:54.386 --> 36:56.257
We're not doing things
the way you used to do them.

36:56.301 --> 36:58.259
Things are changing.

36:58.303 --> 37:01.044
No more hazing probies because
"that's what happened to you."

37:01.088 --> 37:03.090
No more sex jokes.

37:03.133 --> 37:05.658
No more treating this whole
station like it's a frat house.

37:05.701 --> 37:08.313
Under my watch, this house
will feel comfortable

37:08.356 --> 37:10.184
for every person working here.

37:12.404 --> 37:13.796
It was a good call.

37:13.840 --> 37:15.189
No one died,
but we can do better.

37:15.233 --> 37:17.278
And we will do better.

37:17.322 --> 37:18.714
Copy?

37:18.758 --> 37:20.412
-Copy, Captain!
-Copy, Captain.

37:20.455 --> 37:22.240
Maddox, congrats.

37:22.283 --> 37:24.242
You're my new fire prevention
coordinator.

37:24.285 --> 37:25.678
The files are a mess.

37:25.721 --> 37:27.419
It'll take about six to seven
shifts of desk duty

37:27.462 --> 37:29.856
to sort them.

37:29.899 --> 37:31.858
Nowyou're dismissed.

37:31.901 --> 37:36.645
♪♪

37:36.689 --> 37:38.691
I'm writing him up.

37:38.734 --> 37:40.083
I'll leave your name
out of it.

37:40.127 --> 37:41.171
I'm the captain.

37:41.215 --> 37:42.956
It's my job
to look after my team.

37:46.002 --> 37:48.178
Uh, hey -- hey,
you know the drill.

37:48.222 --> 37:50.703
Uh, one thing
you learned today.

37:50.746 --> 37:53.662
Apparently, dolphins sleep
with one eye open.

37:53.706 --> 37:55.273
What?!Where'd you learn that?

37:55.316 --> 37:56.317
TikTok. [ Laughs ]

37:56.361 --> 37:58.101
Ah!
TikTok.
Of course.

37:58.145 --> 37:59.755
Goodness.[ FaceTime ringing ]

37:59.799 --> 38:01.844
Tuck's still at practice,
but we should make him a plate.

38:01.888 --> 38:03.672
It's Ifeya.

38:03.716 --> 38:05.065
[ Ringing continues ]

38:05.108 --> 38:06.501
Answer it.

38:08.590 --> 38:09.504
[ Sighs ]

38:09.548 --> 38:11.289
[ Call chimes ]

38:13.378 --> 38:16.555
Um, good evening,
Dr. Bailey, Dr. Warren.

38:16.598 --> 38:19.035
Um, we, uh...

38:20.559 --> 38:22.517
Arike...

38:22.561 --> 38:26.913
Pru woke up crying,
and asked for Miranda.

38:26.956 --> 38:28.523
Okay, go ahead, Pru.

38:28.567 --> 38:30.351
Say hi.

38:30.395 --> 38:32.788
[ Laughing ]
Hi, there, baby girl!

38:32.832 --> 38:34.355
Shouldn't you
be sleeping?

38:34.399 --> 38:35.704
Don't make me send
Joey over there

38:35.748 --> 38:36.705
to tickle you
back to sleep.

38:36.749 --> 38:38.359
Oh, here.He's right here.

38:38.403 --> 38:40.100
Oh. Hey!

38:40.143 --> 38:42.058
How's it going?
Why aren't you asleep?

38:42.102 --> 38:44.060
[ Pru babbles ]

38:44.104 --> 38:46.846
How about you lay down,
close your eyes,

38:46.889 --> 38:47.977
and we're gonna help you count

38:48.021 --> 38:49.370
all those pandas
on your pajamas.

38:49.414 --> 38:50.850
Bailey: Okay.

38:50.893 --> 38:55.550
[ Together ] One panda,
two pandas, three pandas...

38:55.594 --> 38:57.987
Just because hespeaks
French and Spanish

38:58.031 --> 39:01.077
doesn't mean our baby's
gonna come out speaking
French and Spanish.

39:01.121 --> 39:06.474
♪ I know our love isn't what it
used to be ♪

39:06.518 --> 39:11.174
♪ And now, after all
we've said and done ♪

39:11.218 --> 39:17.137
♪ How do we keep the rising sun
from shutting down? ♪

39:17.180 --> 39:22.490
♪ Are we what
we pretend to be? ♪

39:22.534 --> 39:27.365
♪ And we couldn't find
what we were looking for ♪

39:27.408 --> 39:31.107
♪ We failed to read
the writing on the wall ♪

39:31.151 --> 39:36.374
♪ So, we tried to hold on

39:36.417 --> 39:40.116
♪ Tried to hold on [ Cellphone chimes ]

39:40.160 --> 39:42.728
♪ For they were right

39:42.771 --> 39:44.512
♪ All along

39:44.556 --> 39:46.122
♪ And I couldn't see

39:46.166 --> 39:48.734
♪ I should've let you know

39:48.777 --> 39:53.521
♪ So we tried to hold on

39:53.565 --> 39:58.961
♪ Tried to hold on

39:59.005 --> 40:07.405
♪♪

40:07.448 --> 40:09.189
Sullivan:
Alright, man.

40:09.232 --> 40:10.582
Alright.

40:12.497 --> 40:14.673
Nice speech.

40:14.716 --> 40:18.111
I guess it pays to be
ruthless sometimes.

40:18.154 --> 40:19.852
It wasn't ruthless.
It was right.

40:19.895 --> 40:21.157
Yeah, it was.

40:21.201 --> 40:23.421
I just mean that
being at the top,

40:23.464 --> 40:25.031
to get there and stay there,

40:25.074 --> 40:27.599
you need a little bit
of ruthlessness.

40:27.642 --> 40:29.601
I'm not trying to get and stay
at the top, Robert.

40:29.644 --> 40:31.429
I'm trying to keep
everyone safe.

40:31.472 --> 40:35.215
I don't think about this job
the way you do.

40:35.258 --> 40:37.957
Well, you can try to demonize me
for being ambitious

40:38.000 --> 40:39.828
and wanting my status back,

40:39.872 --> 40:41.047
but you're not being honest
with yourself,

40:41.090 --> 40:42.440
because you want
the same thing.

40:42.483 --> 40:45.268
[ Sighs ]

40:45.312 --> 40:47.270
I saw you
in Beckett's office.

40:47.314 --> 40:49.664
You're starting to feel
the same way I do.

40:49.708 --> 40:52.493
Stuck,
professionally restless.

40:52.537 --> 40:54.495
You know, Aquino could be out
over a year.

40:54.539 --> 40:56.628
If you play your cards right,
this house could be yours.

40:56.671 --> 40:59.065
I would never steal a house
out from under a man

40:59.108 --> 41:01.067
who's been injured
in the line of duty.

41:01.110 --> 41:04.113
I didn't say steal.

41:04.157 --> 41:05.724
You know, this is
Aquino's house to lose.

41:05.767 --> 41:08.074
If you wanted it --I slept with him.

41:10.337 --> 41:11.730
Beckett.

41:11.773 --> 41:14.733
I wasn't trying to get a-a job
or steal anyone's house.

41:14.776 --> 41:17.692
I slept with him once,
and I was letting him down easy.

41:17.736 --> 41:19.128
Okay?

41:19.172 --> 41:25.091
♪♪

41:25.134 --> 41:27.267
[ Quietly ] Okay.

41:27.310 --> 41:28.616
[ Scoffs ]

41:28.660 --> 41:35.536
♪♪

41:35.580 --> 41:42.456
♪♪

41:42.500 --> 41:49.463
♪♪

